USES OF POETRY (mishearing, misunderstanding, mistranslating . . . ), and assigns each of them a tutelary "Ghost-Companion" poet, the teacher recalls wild tales from his coming of age as a poet in the 1960s and 1970s, even as he speculates about the lives and poetic and sexual potential of his twenty-first-century students. From arguing that Allen Ginsberg wasn't actually gay to telling about the time William Burroughs's funeral procession stopped at McDonald's, The Poetry Lesson is a thoroughly entertaining portrait of an inimitable poet, teacher, and storyteller.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aA Coney Island of the Mind.  aAldous Huxley.  aAllen Ginsberg.  aAmiri Baraka.  aAn Embarrassment of Riches.  aAnna Akhmatova.  aAphorism.  aAram Saroyan.  aArthur Rimbaud.  aAubade.  aBarney Rosset.  aBeat Generation.  aBei Dao.  aBertolt Brecht.  aBlack Man.  aBlank verse.  aBoredom.  aBritney Spears.  aCataclysm (Dragonlance).  aCharles Bukowski.  aChe Guevara.  aCunt.  aDe Profundis (letter).  aDeath in Venice.  aDeathbed.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aEmily Dickinson.  aEnglish muffin.  aEzra Pound.  aFeral cat.  aFlapper.  aFrench Colonial.  aFrench Communist Party.  aFrom Beyond the Grave.  aFutility (poem).  aGabriela Mistral.  aGaggle.  aGertrude Stein.  aGregory Corso.  aGuerrilla warfare.  aGuillaume Apollinaire.  aHeir to the Empire.  aHippie.  aHis Family.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIn Another Country.  aIsadora Duncan.  aJack Kerouac.  aJacques Maritain.  aJames Merrill.  aJan Hus.  aJan Kerouac.  aJim Morrison.  aJoan Vollmer.  aJunkie (novel).  aKitsch.  aLawrence Ferlinghetti.  aLibido.  aLord Byron.  aMarilyn Monroe.  aMax Jacob.  aMcSorley's Old Ale House.  aMe